                ArcBest Corporation            








News about ArcBest Corporation, including commentary and archival articles published in The New York Times.                        More









        News about Arkansas Best Corp., including commentary and archival articles published in The New York Times.    




Latest Articles







                    Shippers May Raise Fuel Fees                
Railroads and trucking companies said their first-quarter results were affected by rising fuel costs.










The Boss

                    The Gender Non-Issue                
“I told myself early on that I wasn’t going to make gender an issue in my career or allow other people to do so,” says Judy McReynolds, C.E.O. of the freight company Arkansas Best.











                    National Briefing | Washington: A Vote To Strike                
The Teamsters union said workers voted overwhelmingly to strike against the Roadway Corporation, the Yellow Corporation, the Arkansas Best Corporation and a unit of the USFreightways Corporation if the sides fail to reach agreement on a contract by March 31. Talks between the companies, among the country's largest trucking firms, and the union, which represents 65,000 workers, broke off on Jan. 20 after three months of bargaining. They are to resume on Wednesday.











                    Arkansas Truck Tire Deal                
The Arkansas Best Corporation said today that it had agreed to pay $9 a share, a total of $45.9 million, for the 51 percent of Treadco Inc. it did not already own. Arkansas Best, a trucking company, and Treadco, a retreader and seller of commercial truck tires, are both based in Fort Smith. In Nasdaq trading, the shares of Treadco closed at $8.875, up 18.75 cents, and Arkansas Best was unchanged at $7.5625.










CREDIT MARKETS

                    Arkansas Best's Initial Offering                
The Arkansas Best Corporation, a freight transportation concern based in Fort Smith, Ark., made an initial public offering of 15.7 million common shares yesterday through underwriters led by the First Boston Corporation. The shares were priced at $14 a share, with 10.7 million shares being sold by Arkansas Best and the remaining shares being sold by Kelso Best Partners L.P., which currently owns about 80 percent of the company. Kelso Best Partners has granted the underwriting syndicate an option to buy up to an additional 2,355,000 shares of the company's common stock it owns to cover overallotments. After the offering, about 21.7 percent, or about 11.6 percent if the underwriters exercise their overallotment option in full, will be owned by Kelso Best Partners and approximately 11.5 percent will be owned by management. The company's common stock will be traded on the Nasdaq National Market System under the symbol ABFS.











                    FINANCE BRIEFS                
LEAD: Debt











                    Company News; Arkansas Best Bidding Disputed                
LEAD: The Razorback Acquisition Corporation, bested last week by Kelso & Company in bidding for the Arkansas Best Corporation, said that the competition had been unfair. In a letter to Arkansas Best, a trucking company based in Fort Smith, Ark., Razorback said it was informed by Arkansas Best late last Wednesday that the bid deadline was 6 P.M.











                    COMPANY NEWS: BRIEFS                
LEAD: Arkansas Best Corp., Fort Smith, Ark., a freight transportation company, rejected Razorback Acquisition Corp.'s revised tender offer of $23 a share.










BUSINESS PEOPLE

                    Arkansas Best Suitor Gets Takeover Lesson                
LEAD: Emanuel R. Pearlman, the would-be acquirer of the Arkansas Best Corporation, had been in the takeover business all of 48 hours when he got a strong dose of what lies ahead. The target company ignored his phone calls. The newspapers gave his $230 million deal short shrift. And he balks at the suggestion that he is a corporate raider.











                    Bid Made for Arkansas Best                
LEAD: At a time when many classmates are still paying off the burdensome loans they took out for business school, Emanuel R. Pearlman announced yesterday that he would attempt his first hostile takeover.















                    BRIEFS                
Debt * Arkansas Best Corp. has filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission for $50 million of convertible subordinated debentures due 2011 through Morgan Stanley & Company. * Citicorp sold $50 million of 91-day commercial paper at an average rate of 7.130 percent, down from 7.142 percent last week, and $50 million of 182-day paper at an average rate of 7.019 percent, down from 7.040 percent. * Colonial Bancgroup Inc. is offering $25 million of 7 1/2 percent of convertible subordinated debentures due 2011 at 100 through Merrill Lynch Capital Markets. The debentures are convertible into the company's common stock at $28 a share.


























